      <trans-unit id="6609768968908748834" datatype="html">
        <source> Welcome to Aperture of You. What began as a simple fascination with the camera over 15 years ago has evolved into a dedicated pursuit of portrait photography. Rather than simply taking photographs, I create portraits that capture personality, presence, and character through a distinctive photographic process.</source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">10,12</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="496748652963346100" datatype="html">
        <source>The Process</source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">14,15</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="8620481688257990932" datatype="html">
        <source>The mosaic panorama technique</source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">15,17</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="5198658410212708138" datatype="html">
        <source> The true distinction of my work lies in the way each portrait is created. Rather than relying on a single exposure, I carefully capture and combine multiple photographs into one seamless mosaic panorama. <x id="LINE_BREAK" ctype="lb" equiv-text="&lt;br&gt;"/><x id="LINE_BREAK" ctype="lb" equiv-text="&lt;br&gt;"/> The result is a portrait that combines the character of vintage optics with the precision of modern digital techniques. This approach produces images with extraordinary detail, remarkable depth, and an immersive, almost three-dimensional perspective. </source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">18,23</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="95294165850169434" datatype="html">
        <source>The soul of it all, a 1957 Carl Zeiss Jena Biotar.</source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">35,37</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="1385616436544845921" datatype="html">
        <source> Every photographer develops their own visual signature. Mine is defined in part by my choice of lens – a beautiful piece of imperfection, produced in 1957. Contemporary lenses are engineered for technical perfection; mine brings character, subtle imperfections, and a distinctive rendering that gives each image a unique visual identity. </source>
        <context-group purpose="location">
          <context context-type="sourcefile">src/app/pages/home/home.html</context>
          <context context-type="linenumber">38,40</context>
        </context-group>
      </trans-unit>
